Well also provide you with a repository of links that can be accessed to further your learning with Hedera on your own accord as well as to interact with the Hedera community and keep up to date by following Hederas social channels.

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: What is Hedera?
Hedera is an open-source, decentralized public ledger powered by a unique proof-of-stake method that employs the advanced, leaderless aBFT hashgraph consensus mechanism. A diverse, decentralized council of top-tier enterprises, academia, and cutting-edge web3 entities globally oversee its operations.
Taking advantage of the performance-enhanced Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) for smart contracts, coupled with intuitive APIs for native tokenization and consensus services, Hedera empowers developers to craft the next-generation web3 platforms and applications reshaping the internet's future.

Setting itself apart from traditional blockchains, Hedera boasts rapid transaction speeds with instant finality, consistent and affordable fees, and fair transaction sequencing through consensus timestamps. Its solid foundation ensures unparalleled scalability and dependability across all network levels. Furthermore, with governance by a coalition of global frontrunners, Hedera guarantees resistance against collusion.
Step 2: What is Hashgraph?
Hashgraph In the previous step, we mentioned that Hedera is powered by the Hashgraph consensus algorithm. Lets find out more about what this powerful algorithm is!

Hashgraph is both a distributed consensus algorithm where nodes can communicate with one another and also a data structure for grouping transactions together. This unique network design allows for desirable properties such as fairness, security, and high throughput. Hashgraph relies on Gossip about Gossip and the Virtual Voting mechanism to bring consensus to the network. Well cover those in a bit, but first, lets take a look at how the Hashgraph works!



Watch the video above to get an overview of how the Hashgraph consensus algorithm works. Below is a summary of some of the points covered in the video:
  • Messages (or events as they are also called) are sent between nodes in the network via the Gossip protocol
  • The order of messages in a network is agreed upon by getting the median timestamp in which nodes in the network received the message
  • Each message has the following components - transactions, timestamp, (cryptographic) signature, a hash of the last message the node made (self-parent), and a hash of the last message the node received (other-parent)
Step 3: Gossip About Gossip & Virtual Voting
Gossip about Gossip The term Gossip about Gossip was covered in the video in the previous step. Lets dive a bit deeper into what this refers to!

Gossip about Gossip is a term in which nodes in a Hashgraph network exchange information (events) among themselves. These events are related to each other, resulting in a directed acyclic graph (DAG). When two nodes communicate, they exchange information about the events they have seen and heard about, and this information is used to update their respective records with synchronised information - this is called a Gossip Sync. Refer here to find out more about Gossip about Gossip.

Virtual Voting
Virtual voting is a term used to describe the process by which nodes in a Hashgraph come to a consensus about the order of events that have occurred within the system. The hashgraph algorithm does not require any votes to be sent across the network to calculate the votes of each member. Members can calculate every other members votes by internally looking at each of their copies of the hashgraph and applying the virtual voting algorithm. 

Votes are calculated locally as a function of the ancestors of a given event. This virtual voting has several benefits. In addition to saving bandwidth, it ensures that members always calculate their votes according to the rules in a leaderless manner. Virtual voting happens in 3 steps: Divide Rounds, Decide Fame and Find Order. 

First, the events are divided into rounds. Then, each node will vote on which event should qualify as a famous witness. The events that have already been voted on would be ordered based on the median timestamp for each event (as evaluated from the timestamps collected for that event across all nodes). Refer here if you would like to read more about virtual voting.
Step 4: Hedera Network Services
The Hedera network services are a set of application programming interfaces (APIs) that allow developers to conveniently interact with the Hedera network. Some of these functions include creating accounts, minting tokens, writing data to the ledger, interacting with smart contracts, etc.
Each API call has a predictable transaction fee based on the processing and storage required. The various Hedera SDKs available make it easy to access the APIs in your favourite programming language including JavaScript, Java, and Go. 

There are three core Hedera network services - 1) Hedera Token Service (HTS), 2) Hedera Consensus Service (HCS) and 3) Hedera Smart Contract Service (HSCS). Lets find out more about each of them below!

Hedera Token Service
HTS allows users to manage, configure, and transfer tokens on Hedera. It provides an easy and flexible experience when working with tokenization on Hedera. HTS offers incredibly high-throughput, low fees, and compliance configurations. There's even on-chain programmability, with API calls for atomic swaps and royalties, among other features.

Hedera Consensus Service
HCS is a consensus-as-a-service platform that is built on the Hedera network. It is a tool for creating decentralized, auditable logs of immutable and timestamped events for both Web2 and Web3 apps by using the Hashgraph consensus algorithm. HCS combines the trust of Hederas public network, with the privacy of permissioned blockchain frameworks so it enables verifiable timestamps, decentralized ordering, and privacy for sensitive information. 

Hedera Smart Contract Service
Smart contracts on Hedera are Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) compatible; this means that smart contracts on Hedera can be built using Solidity. Smart contracts on Hedera are optimized for hashgraph. With hashgraph efficiency, your contracts run fast with finality in seconds, carbon-negative energy use, and always predictable gas fees. Because the smart contract calls execute on top of the Hashgraph consensus mechanism, calls are executed in the order they are received, not the amount of gas paid. HSCS can also manage tokens on Hedera using HTS to deliver automated token management capabilities.

Since the Hedera network services are an integral part of building on Hedera, well be deep diving into each of these network services in the subsequent quests of this campaign, so stay tuned!
Step 5: Hedera Governing Council
The Hedera Governing Council is a group of up to 39 highly diversified organizations responsible for governing the Hedera Hashgraph distributed ledger platform. They make decisions by a majority vote and provide guidance on the direction of the platform. Some notable organisations that sit on the council include Google, IBM, Boeing, Chainlink Labs etc. Refer to the image below to view the other organisations that make up the governing council.


Hedera addresses decentralization concerns by separating governance from consensus. Hedera's governance design assures no single company, small group of developers, or node operators has undue influence or control over the network. All council members have a three-year maximum term, with up to two consecutive terms and an equal vote on network and platform decisions.

The following are some of the benefits of Hederas decentralized governance model:
  • Codebase direction - all council members share an equal vote in the direction of Hedera's software and services. Hedera Improvement Proposals are used for community input
  • Network stability - Hedera has a no-fork guarantee. The Hedera Governing Council achieves this through technical controls via state proofs
  • Decentralized nodes - Although the council members run the initial set of nodes on the Hedera network, the Hedera network infrastructure can scale to support up to thousands of public nodes joining in the networks consensus
  • Fair responsibility - All members have a three-year maximum term, with up to two consecutive terms and an equal vote on network and platform decisions. Swirlds, the creator of hashgraph, has a permanent seat and equal vote

Lets go through some of the key developer resources that we recommend you bookmark as you embark on your developer journey on Hedera.

Developer Tooling & Integrations - this is a repository of microservice APIs, network gateways, payment rails, integrations, and plugins to help build applications on Hedera

Whitepapers - a list of whitepapers created by Hedera that detail its technology and economic decision making

Bug Bounty Program - earn rewards from finding bugs on Hedera and submitting reports

Grants & Accelerators - the Hedera ecosystem offers grant programs and accelerators for developers building on Hedera

Step 9: Summary
Weve learnt quite a bit about Hedera in this quest! In the next quest, well cover more core concepts that one should know of when building on Hedera. But for now, lets go through a summary of some of the points weve just learnt before we end the quest.
  1. Hedera is an open-source decentralized public network that is powered by Hashgraph and allows developers to create and deploy dApps with high throughput, low latency, and security
  2. Hashgraph is an open-source consensus algorithm and data structure that is used by the Hedera Network to provide fast, secure, and fair consensus. It uses Gossip about Gossip and virtual voting to reach consensus
    • Gossip about Gossip is where nodes on the network share information with other nodes in the network which results in the data structure forming a DAG
    • Virtual voting is a term used to describe the process by which nodes in a Hashgraph come to a consensus about determining the order in which transactions and other events are processed on the network
  3. The Hedera network services are a set of APIs that allow developers to conveniently interact with the Hedera network. They consist of:
    • Hedera Token Service allows users to manage, configure, and transfer tokens on Hedera. It provides an easy and flexible experience when working with tokenization on Hedera
    • Hedera Consensus Service is a consensus platform that is built on the Hedera network. It is a tool for creating decentralized, auditable logs of immutable and timestamped events for both Web2 and Web3 apps by using the Hashgraph consensus algorithm
    • Hedera Smart Contract Service allows developers to build Solidity smart contracts on Hedera that run fast, with finality in seconds, have carbon-negative energy use, and predictable gas fees
  4. Hedera Governing Council is a group of leading organizations that are responsible for governing the Hedera Hashgraph Distributed Ledger Platform by making decisions based on majority vote and providing guidance on the direction and growth of the Hedera Platform
